\begin{abstract}
Clinical AI systems are physically situated agents: their diagnostic
decisions lead directly to physical interventions, and their errors
cause physiological harm. Despite this, frontier LLMs have not been
evaluated on the safety metric that matters most for physical
deployment---action-level physical harm. We present a systematic
evaluation of four frontier LLMs (GPT-5, Llama-3.3-70B,
Llama-4-Scout, and Qwen2.5-32B) using the Med-Guard Evaluation
Framework, which extends our prior system~\cite{jain2024medguard}
with an LLM patient simulator, dynamic EMR injection, and physical
harm metrics. Evaluating on 50 USMLE-style cases per model, we
discover two structurally distinct failure modes. \emph{Active}
models (GPT-5, Qwen2.5-32B) make frequent clinical decisions but
are severely miscalibrated and unsafe: GPT-5 achieves 62\% accuracy
but leaves dangerous wrong-diagnosis actions unintercepted in 16\%
of cases; Qwen2.5-32B acts prematurely in 24\% of cases with the
highest missed harm rate (22\%). \emph{Passive} models
(Llama-3.3-70B, Llama-4-Scout) never attempt prescriptions and
achieve near-zero action-level harm---but only because they fail to
reach a diagnosis in 46--50\% of cases, leaving patients without
any clinical decision. All four models are severely miscalibrated
(ECE\,=\,0.246--0.523), making confidence-threshold safety
guardrails structurally insufficient. No model meets a reasonable
safety threshold for autonomous clinical deployment.
\end{abstract}

%───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
\section{Introduction}

Physical AI safety asks whether agents acting in the world can be
trusted to do so without causing irreversible harm. Robots, autonomous
vehicles, and clinical AI systems share the same structural property:
their decisions have direct physical consequences, their errors are
measurable, and their deployment requires safety guarantees that go
beyond average performance~\cite{alshiekh2018safe}. For the first
two, decades of work have produced runtime verification, safety
shielding, and uncertainty quantification frameworks that intercept
dangerous actions before they reach the physical
system~\cite{angelopoulos2021conformal}. Clinical AI has received no
equivalent treatment. Its evaluation literature measures diagnostic
accuracy, not physical harm.

This gap is consequential. LLMs capable of multi-turn medical
reasoning are actively under consideration for clinical
deployment~\cite{wang2025survey}. A system that is 62\% accurate
sounds promising---until one asks what it \emph{does} in the 38\% of
cases it gets wrong, and whether any safety mechanism stops it. Our
prior work, Med-Guard~\cite{jain2024medguard}, built a multi-agent
clinical system with dedicated safety agents and a self-correcting
prescription loop, demonstrating improved diagnostic accuracy and
prescription safety. Here we repurpose that architecture as an
evaluation framework and apply it to four frontier models: GPT-5
(Azure OpenAI), Llama-3.3-70B, Llama-4-Scout, and Qwen2.5-32B
(Groq).

The results reveal something more complex---and more concerning---than
a simple ranking of models by safety. The four systems exhibit two
fundamentally different failure modes that are both incompatible with
safe autonomous deployment. GPT-5 and Qwen2.5-32B are
\emph{overconfident actors}: they commit to diagnoses and act on
them, frequently and under-evidenced, producing physical harm that
safety guardrails cannot reliably intercept. Llama-3.3-70B and
Llama-4-Scout are \emph{paralysed abstainers}: they avoid commitment
entirely, achieving near-zero action-level harm not through safe
decision-making but by failing to reach any clinical decision in
46--50\% of cases. A patient who receives no diagnosis is not helped.
A system that never acts is not safe---it is useless.

Across all four models, ECE ranges from 0.246 to 0.523, against a
safe-deployment threshold of $<$0.05. This means that for every
model tested, the model's expressed confidence cannot be used as a
reliable safety signal. The safety guardrail we evaluate---which is
architecturally equivalent to the safety shields used in robotics and
autonomous systems research---fails to intercept dangerous actions on
incorrect diagnoses for this fundamental reason: overconfident wrong
decisions and overconfident correct decisions are indistinguishable by
threshold logic.

\textbf{Contributions:}
(1)~The Med-Guard Evaluation Framework, extending our prior
system~\cite{jain2024medguard} with physical harm metrics and
support for multi-model evaluation.
(2)~The first comparative action-level safety evaluation of four
frontier LLMs in interactive clinical diagnosis.
(3)~Identification of two distinct failure modes---active-unsafe
and passive-useless---both of which preclude safe autonomous
deployment.
(4)~Evidence that confidence-threshold guardrails are structurally
insufficient across all four model families, motivating calibration-
aware and evidence-grounded safety architectures.

