\section{Related Work}

\textbf{Physical AI safety.}
Safety shielding intercepts agent actions against formal
specifications before execution~\cite{alshiekh2018safe}. Conformal
prediction and Bayesian uncertainty quantification bound agent
confidence to prevent dangerous overreach~\cite{angelopoulos2021conformal}.
These techniques share a common structure: monitor the agent's
intended action, assess its safety, and block or modify if necessary.
Our guardrail follows this pattern. Our central finding---that
this pattern fails when agent confidence does not track epistemic
uncertainty---has implications for any physically situated system
whose internal signals are miscalibrated.

\textbf{LLM-based clinical agents.}
AgentClinic~\cite{schmidgall2025agentclinic} demonstrated that
structured multi-agent workflows improve diagnostic accuracy. MDAgents~\cite{kim2024mdagents}
and MEDDxAgent~\cite{rose2025meddxagent} showed further gains through
adaptive collaboration. Our prior Med-Guard system~\cite{jain2024medguard}
introduced dedicated safety agents. All of this work focuses on
accuracy and output quality. The present paper shifts focus to
action-level physical harm: not what models say, but what they do.

\textbf{Clinical AI safety evaluation.}
MedSafetyBench~\cite{han2024medsafety} and red-teaming
work~\cite{balazadeh2025redteam} evaluate whether models refuse to
produce harmful text---output-level safety. MedSentry~\cite{chen2025medsentry}
taxonomises failure modes in multi-agent systems. These contributions
measure the wrong variable: a model that confidently prescribes the
wrong drug produces no harmful text and would pass every existing
benchmark. It would harm the patient. We measure the actions.

\textbf{Confidence calibration.}
Guo et al.~\cite{guo2017calibration} established that modern neural
networks are overconfident and proposed temperature scaling as a
remedy. Kadavath et al.~\cite{kadavath2022know} showed LLMs degrade
in calibration near their competence boundary. Our results---ECE
0.246--0.523 across four models in clinical reasoning---extend
these findings to interactive multi-turn diagnosis and demonstrate
their safety implications directly.

