\section{The Med-Guard Evaluation Framework}

\subsection{Clinical Encounter Simulation}

We simulate complete multi-turn clinical encounters because static
QA benchmarks cannot reveal whether a model acts prematurely, whether
its confidence tracks the evidence it has actually gathered, or whether
safety mechanisms can intercept dangerous decisions. Each encounter
runs for up to 10 turns across four components.

\textbf{Doctor Agent.} The model under evaluation, prompted as a
clinician. At every turn it produces free-text reasoning plus three
mandatory structured fields:

\vspace{2pt}
{\small\texttt{DIAGNOSIS:~<disease~or~``unknown''>}\\
\texttt{CONFIDENCE:~<0.0--1.0>}\\
\texttt{ACTION:~<from~the~fixed~action~space>}}
\vspace{2pt}

\noindent The action space is:
\{\texttt{ask\_question}, \texttt{order\_lab\_test},
\texttt{order\_imaging}, \texttt{prescribe\_medication},
\texttt{prescribe\_high\_risk\_medication},
\texttt{admit\_patient}, \texttt{refer\_specialist},
\texttt{discharge}, \texttt{advise\_followup}\}.
Structured output makes the intended physical action unambiguous
at every turn.

\textbf{Patient Agent.} A GPT-5 instance holding the hidden clinical
profile, used identically across all model evaluations to isolate the
Doctor Agent as the variable under study. Unlike the template-based
patient simulator in AgentClinic~\cite{schmidgall2025agentclinic},
it responds only to what the doctor actually asked, generating
natural language conditioned on the question and enforcing genuine
information asymmetry.

\textbf{Measurement Agent.} A GPT-5 instance that intercepts the
doctor's output each turn, cross-references explicit test requests
against available clinical data, and returns only the requested
results---withholding everything else. It records per-turn counts of
tests requested versus found, producing per-case diagnostic
precision scores.

\textbf{Correctness evaluation.} Two-stage: string normalisation
with hedge-word stripping, followed by LLM-based clinical equivalence
judgment prompted with: \emph{``Return True only if a clinician
would treat these as the same working diagnosis and the initial
management plan would be identical.''} A \texttt{startswith(``true'')}
check prevents false positives from phrases such as ``not true.''

Encounters terminate early at confidence $\geq 0.8$ after at least
three turns. Three consecutive identical actions trigger a system
override forcing a final decision.

\subsection{Dataset}

We use AgentClinic-MedQA~\cite{schmidgall2025agentclinic}, 50 cases
per model. Results should be treated as preliminary; a full 200-case
evaluation is in progress.

\subsection{Safety Metrics}

All metrics answer: \emph{what would happen to a real patient?}

\textbf{Physical harm scores.} Each action is assigned a score 0--4
based on patient risk if taken on an incorrect diagnosis
(Table~\ref{tab:harm}). The scale maps to the severity tiers of the
NCC MERP Medication Error Index~\cite{nccmerp2001} and AHRQ Common
Formats~\cite{ahrq2019}. Scores are expert-assigned; clinical
validation is ongoing.

