\subsection{Two Failure Modes}

Fig.~\ref{fig:clusters} plots each model's accuracy against its
EPH\_intended and reveals an immediate clustering. GPT-5 and
Qwen2.5-32B occupy the upper-right region: high EPH (2.12--2.16),
active clinical decision-making, and non-zero HHM (16--22\%). These
are \emph{overconfident actors}---models that commit to diagnoses
and act on them frequently, with insufficient accuracy and safety
guardrails that cannot reliably intercept dangerous errors.

Llama-3.3-70B and Llama-4-Scout occupy the lower-left region: EPH
below 0.30 and HHM of 0\%. At first glance this looks safe. It is
not. These models fail to reach a confident diagnosis in 46--50\% of
cases (23 and 25 of 50 respectively), exhausting the 10-turn budget
without committing to any action. Their Rx attempt rate is 0\%---they
never prescribe. Their decision delay of 9.86--9.96 turns means they
almost always reach the turn limit before deciding. These are
\emph{paralysed abstainers}: they achieve low EPH not through
accurate safe decisions but through systematic avoidance of clinical
commitment. A patient who receives no diagnosis and no treatment is
not helped. A system that avoids harm by refusing to act is useless
in the same way an autonomous vehicle that refuses to move is
``safe'' only in a trivial sense.

\subsection{Calibration: A Universal Failure}

Fig.~\ref{fig:calibration} shows that all four models are severely
miscalibrated. ECE ranges from 0.246 (GPT-5) to 0.523
(Llama-3.3-70B), against a safe-deployment threshold of $<$0.05---a
factor of 5--10 above what safety-critical systems should achieve.

The nature of the miscalibration differs between clusters. For
active models (GPT-5, Qwen), the problem is overconfidence in the
0.80--0.90 band: at expressed confidence 0.85, actual accuracy is
approximately 52\%. For passive models (Llama variants), the problem
manifests differently---average confidence is lower (0.738) but
accuracy is 24--28\%, so miscalibration extends across more of the
confidence range. Both types make the same safety mechanism unreliable.

The OER of 20--28\% across all models means that roughly one in four
cases involves a high-confidence wrong diagnosis. These are the
cases that confidence-threshold guardrails cannot intercept by
construction: the model produces the same confidence score whether
it is correct or not.

\subsection{Action-Level Physical Harm}

For active models, EPH\_intended of 2.12--2.16 reflects systematic
bias toward high-risk interventions. The guardrail reduces this by
13\% (GPT-5) and 26\% (Qwen2.5-32B), yielding EPH\_realized of
1.58--1.88. Qwen's higher EPH reduction (26\%) reflects more
guardrail interventions (UAR 20\% vs GPT-5's 12\%)---but its HHM is
worse (22\% vs 16\%), because the guardrail triggers on prescription
safety failures while missing the more dangerous pattern of
premature committed wrong diagnoses. Qwen's decision delay of 4.3
turns and premature action rate of 24\% mean it reaches clinical
decisions before gathering adequate evidence, resulting in the
worst high-harm miss rate of any model.

For passive models, EPH\_intended is near zero (0.26--0.28) because
ask\_question carries harm score 0 and these models almost never
leave this action. Their HHM of 0\% is therefore not a safety
achievement---it is a consequence of clinical passivity. Reporting
HHM alone would incorrectly classify Llama-3.3-70B as the safest
model. Reporting it alongside the 50\% never-diagnosed rate and
zero Rx attempts reveals the real picture.

\subsection{Diagnostic Test Ordering}

An interesting reversal appears in diagnostic precision. GPT-5,
despite the highest accuracy, has the worst precision (0.41):
it requests 5.54 tests per case but only 1.54 are in the record.
Passive models show better precision (0.62--0.64) because they
order tests across all 50 cases (cases\_with\_tests\,=\,50) but
with fewer, more targeted requests (3.8 per case). This suggests
GPT-5 generates broad clinical workups from prior knowledge rather
than reasoning tightly from available evidence, while Llama models
probe more selectively but then fail to commit on the basis of
results. Neither represents ideal clinical behaviour.

\subsection{Failure Mode Taxonomy}

Classifying incorrect diagnoses reveals four types consistent across
active models. \textbf{Symptom overlap} ($\sim$37\%): correct symptom
cluster, wrong aetiology (e.g., Hirschsprung disease diagnosed as
intussusception). \textbf{Complication confusion} ($\sim$21\%): model
identifies a complication rather than the root cause (e.g., lung
cancer diagnosed as acute CO poisoning via SIADH). \textbf{High-harm
miss} ($\sim$21\%): wrong diagnosis, high-harm action, no guardrail
intervention---the directly dangerous failures. \textbf{Clinically
adjacent} ($\sim$21\%): predictions differing by specificity; some
may be LLM-judge errors. Passive models show a different profile:
their errors are dominated by failure to converge, not
misdiagnosis---they run out of turns before committing.

