\section{Discussion}

\subsection{Why Neither Cluster Is Safe}

The active-passive split makes visible a tradeoff that previous
accuracy-only evaluations could not reveal. A model evaluated on
accuracy alone might prefer GPT-5 (62\%) over Llama-3.3-70B (24\%).
A model evaluated on HHM alone might prefer Llama (0\%) over GPT-5
(16\%). Neither conclusion is correct for deployment. GPT-5 is
accurate but takes dangerous wrong actions 16\% of the time without
any safety mechanism to stop it. Llama-3.3-70B avoids dangerous
actions by avoiding all actions---it is clinically inert in half of
cases. Both are unsafe. Both are unsuitable for autonomous
deployment. The failure modes are different in mechanism but
equivalent in consequence: patients are harmed in the first case
and abandoned in the second.

This finding motivates a composite safety metric. A deployable
clinical AI system must satisfy three properties simultaneously:
sufficient diagnostic accuracy, acceptable EPH after guardrail
intervention, and a bounded never-diagnosed rate. No current model
satisfies all three.

\subsection{The Guardrail's Structural Limitation}

The guardrail reduces EPH for active models (13--26\%) but catches
zero dangerous wrong-diagnosis actions for GPT-5 across both this
run and prior evaluations. The reason is architectural: the guardrail
monitors expressed confidence, which does not track correctness in
the 0.80--0.90 range where most decisions fall. An overconfident
wrong decision looks identical to an overconfident correct decision
from the guardrail's perspective. This is not a flaw in the specific
rules---it is the expected behaviour of threshold logic applied to
a miscalibrated signal.

Three directions follow. \emph{Post-hoc calibration}~\cite{guo2017calibration}:
remapping expressed confidence to empirical accuracy before threshold
evaluation would lower the effective threshold for the overconfident
0.85 band. \emph{Evidence-grounded action verification}: assessing
whether the chosen action is consistent with the evidence gathered
during the encounter, without requiring ground truth.
\emph{Dual-agent verification}: a second independent agent
evaluating the case and flagging disagreement, replicating clinical
second-opinion protocols.

\subsection{Implications for Physical AI Safety}

The two failure modes---overconfident actor and paralysed
abstainer---are not unique to clinical AI. They describe a general
tension in any physically situated AI system: acting confidently
enough to be useful while being uncertain enough to be safe. The
clinical domain makes this tension measurable because actions are
classifiable and harm is quantifiable. Safety shields in robotics
face the same underlying problem when applied to agents whose
confidence does not track uncertainty~\cite{alshiekh2018safe}.
Our evaluation framework offers a template for action-level safety
assessment that generalises beyond healthcare.

\subsection{Limitations}

Harm scores are ordinal and expert-assigned; clinical validation
is a priority. The 50-case evaluation per model is preliminary;
the full 200-case evaluation is underway. The Patient and
Measurement Agents use GPT-5 across all runs, which may advantage
GPT-5 as the Doctor Agent. AgentClinic-MedQA cases may be more
archetypal than real clinical presentations.

