\section{Conclusion}

We evaluated four frontier LLMs---GPT-5, Llama-3.3-70B,
Llama-4-Scout, and Qwen2.5-32B---on action-level physical safety in
interactive clinical diagnosis. The results reveal two failure modes
that are both incompatible with safe autonomous deployment. Active
models act frequently but unsafely: GPT-5 achieves 62\% accuracy
but leaves dangerous wrong-diagnosis actions unintercepted in 16\%
of cases; Qwen2.5-32B acts prematurely in 24\% of cases with the
highest harm miss rate. Passive models avoid dangerous actions only
by avoiding all actions: Llama-3.3-70B and Llama-4-Scout never
diagnose 46--50\% of patients. All four models are severely
miscalibrated (ECE\,=\,0.246--0.523), making confidence-threshold
safety guardrails structurally inadequate. Accuracy alone cannot
reveal these failure modes; physical harm metrics are necessary.
Clinical AI systems are physically situated agents, and they should
be held to the safety standards that physical AI safety research has
established for other embodied systems.


\section{Human Evaluation}
\label{sec:human_eval}

To validate our automated evaluation, we conducted a human study
with clinical domain experts across three languages:
\textbf{Tamil}, \textbf{Kannada}, and \textbf{Hindi}---spanning
Dravidian (medium-resource) and Indo-Aryan (high-resource) families.
For each language, annotators evaluated zero-shot and few-shot
summaries using the same three-dimensional rubric as our LLM judge:
Truthfulness, Safety, and Explainability (1--5 Likert scale), plus
an Overall trust rating.

\paragraph{Results.}
Table~\ref{tab:human_eval} reports mean scores for Tamil; Kannada
and Hindi show consistent trends. Across all three languages,
human annotators assign \textit{lower} scores than the LLM judge,
particularly on Safety and Trustworthiness, suggesting that our
automated scores may \emph{overestimate} clinical reliability.
Zero-shot outperforms few-shot on factual accuracy (3 vs.\ 2) and
overall trust (2 vs.\ 3), consistent with our automated findings.
Annotators noted that few-shot summaries ``provide a good overall
view of the conversation'' but contain misleading clinical details,
while zero-shot summaries preserve more clinical facts but miss the
broader conversational context.

The most notable finding is the Safety--Explainability divergence:
few-shot summaries score higher on explainability (4 vs.\ 3) but
lower on factual accuracy (2 vs.\ 3). This mirrors the quantitative
pattern observed in entity-level metrics, where few-shot outputs
are more structured but less faithful---and validates that LLM-judge
safety scores, while correlated with human ratings, do not fully
capture the clinical risk perceived by domain experts.

