\begin{abstract}
Clinical AI systems are overwhelmingly benchmarked in English, yet a billion-plus speakers of Indian languages rely on healthcare systems where consultations happen in diverse regional languages. We study whether current open-source LLMs can generate trustworthy English clinical summaries directly from multilingual doctor-patient dialogues, a practically important setting that has received almost no systematic attention. We evaluate two 7B-parameter LLMs (Mistral-7B and Qwen2.5-7B) across ten typologically diverse Indian languages under four conditions: zero-shot prompting, few-shot prompting ($k{=}1$), translation of source dialogues to English via IndicTrans2 before summarization, and LoRA-based supervised fine-tuning (SFT).

We find that few-shot prompting \emph{degrades} performance in 16 of 20 language--model pairs; translation helps Indo-Aryan but harms Dravidian languages; and clinical Safety scores remain below 3.0/5.0 across every condition. Fine-tuning eliminates the cross-lingual performance gap---post-SFT Dravidian F1 reaches parity with English---while reducing macro-average hallucination from $\sim$42\% to $\sim$10\%. We additionally conduct systematic qualitative case analysis across all ten languages, yielding an eight-category Clinical Error Taxonomy that characterizes failure modes by method and language family.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}
The accurate and timely documentation of clinical encounters is a cornerstone of modern healthcare delivery. Clinical consultations between doctors and patients typically contain a rich mix of essential details---including symptoms, diagnostic reasoning, medication histories, treatment decisions, and relevant psycho-social context. All of these are vital for accurate documentation and continuity of care, yet much of this content is never reliably captured in structured clinical records.

In India alone, primary healthcare workers conduct hundreds of millions of consultations annually across a population that speaks 22 constitutionally scheduled languages spanning four major language families \citep{gala2023indictrans2}. The cognitive burden of manual documentation in this setting is substantial, and errors of omission in clinical notes are well-documented as a leading source of adverse patient outcomes \citep{clusmann2023future}. Automatic summarization of clinical dialogues using large language models (LLMs) offers a promising path toward reducing this burden. Recent work demonstrates that instruction-tuned LLMs achieve competitive performance on English clinical summarization benchmarks \citep{tang2023gersteinlab, abacha2023overview}. However, the overwhelming majority of clinical NLP research targets high-resource languages---most often English---leaving a vast multilingual clinical documentation need unaddressed. Real-world healthcare delivery frequently occurs in multilingual and low-resource linguistic environments. For Indian languages, which range from relatively well-resourced Indo-Aryan languages (Hindi, Bengali) to morphologically complex (Marathi) and script-distinct Dravidian languages (Telugu, Tamil, Kannada), existing LLM-based summarization pipelines are entirely unevaluated.

This paper addresses that gap through a systematic benchmarking study of multilingual clinical dialogue summarization across \textbf{ten typologically diverse Indian languages} (Table~\ref{tab:language_data}). The languages span five script families, two major typological groupings (Indo-Aryan and Dravidian), and a spectrum of NLP resource availability. We analyze the trustworthiness of cross-lingual clinical summarization systems, focusing on truthfulness, safety, and explainability, to examine how linguistic and resource differences influence quality. To our knowledge, this is the first systematic study characterizing trustworthiness failures in multilingual clinical dialogue summarization for Indic languages. We benchmark two open-source instruction-tuned 7B-parameter models, Mistral-7B~\citep{jiang2023mistral} and Qwen2.5-7B~\citep{qwen25techreport}, under four paradigms: zero-shot prompting, few-shot prompting, translation-augmented inference via IndicTrans2~\citep{gala2023indictrans2}, and supervised fine-tuning. Evaluation spans surface-level metrics, LLM-as-judge holistic assessment~\citep{zheng2023judging}, and clinical entity-level fidelity analysis. 

Our principal contributions are: \textbf{(1)} The first systematic study of open-source LLMs on cross-lingual clinical dialogue summarization across ten Indian languages (four Dravidian, six Indo-Aryan). \textbf{(2)} Evidence that Qwen2.5-7B outperforms Mistral-7B on every entity-level metric in zero-shot scenarios, traced to Qwen2.5's broader multilingual pretraining over Indic scripts. \textbf{(3)} A finding that supervised fine-tuning substantially improves clinical safety, truthfulness, explainability, and entity-level precision/recall across all language families while drastically lowering hallucinations and omissions.

\section{Related Work}
The automatic summarization of doctor-patient conversation has emerged as a central task in clinical NLP. Early work applied extractive and abstractive sequence-to-sequence models to English medical conversations, achieving competitive performance on structured note generation \citep{joshi2020dr,abacha2023empirical}. The MEDIQA-Chat 2023 shared task~\citep{abacha2023overview} catalyzed a wave of systems utilizing in-context learning with GPT-3 and GPT-4. \citet{tang2023gersteinlab} demonstrated strong ROUGE-1 and BERTScore with fine-tuned GPT-3 and few-shot GPT-4, while \citet{mathur2023summqa} found that GPT-4 generated summaries tend to be shorter and more abstractive than human-authored notes, highlighting a systematic coverage gap directly replicated in our multilingual setting. 

More recent work evaluates LLMs as clinical summarizers. \citet{vanveen2023adapted} showed domain-adapted LLMs can outperform medical experts on English benchmarks. \citet{FraileNavarro2025} and \citet{Ferreira2025} evaluated LLMs on real-world non-English data (Portuguese), finding open-source LLMs struggle with informal, noisy patient-provider dialogues---a challenge amplified in our setting by script diversity. \citet{zeng2020meddialog} introduced one of the first datasets covering both English and Chinese, while \citet{lyu2025automatic} explored prompt tuning on domain-specific LLMs. Clinical NLP in multilingual settings has primarily focused on entity recognition rather than summarization \cite{gaschi2023multilingual}. \citet{abrar2025faithful} proposed a cross-lingual framework for consumer health queries using extraction and finetuned LLMs. 

Indian languages present distinctive challenges. \citet{gala2023indictrans2} introduced IndicTrans2, the first neural machine translation system supporting all 22 scheduled Indian languages, remaining the state-of-the-art translation backbone. For clinical NLP specifically, \citet{singh2025indihealthbench} evaluated LLMs for clinical translation across Indian languages, finding performance degrades sharply for Dravidian and low-resource Indo-Aryan languages, consistent with the zero-shot performance gaps we report.

