\subsection{Fine-Tuning Closes the Cross-Lingual Gap}
\label{sec:sft}
SFT produces the strongest results across every metric. The largest gains go to the lowest-performing languages (Mistral-Telugu +0.487 F1). Post-SFT, Dravidian languages reach near-parity with high-resource Indo-Aryan languages, proving the performance gap is an artifact of task-training, not inherent linguistic limits. Hallucination drops from 42.4\% to 10.5\% (Qwen), with every language achieving $<14.5\%$ hallucination. 

\textbf{Qwen vs. Mistral:} At zero-shot, Qwen2.5-7B heavily outperforms Mistral-7B due to its broader multilingual Indic pretraining. Post-SFT, the gap narrows to near-zero (0.775 vs 0.760 F1), indicating both architectures have comparable capacity once explicitly aligned to the task.

\textbf{Safety is Hardest to Improve:} Safety is the lowest-scoring dimension everywhere, failing to reach 3.0/5.0 even post-SFT. Crucially, the gap between Truthfulness and Safety \emph{widens} under SFT (0.76 to 1.19 for Qwen). Standard SFT teaches accurate-sounding content but does not penalize dangerous omissions or inverted negations. Closing this gap requires explicit safety-targeted reward modeling.

\section{Clinical Error Taxonomy}
Our systematic qualitative analysis across all ten languages identified eight recurring error mechanisms, varying by condition:
\noindent\textbf{T1 -- Temporal distortion:} Numerals extract correctly but units are substituted (e.g., three months becomes three days). Common in low-resource zero-shot due to weak tokenization.
\noindent\textbf{T2 -- Pathology fabrication:} Clinically plausible but invented diagnoses (e.g., generating an ``apnea episode'' for throat discomfort). Common when low-confidence Dravidian ZS relies on pretraining priors.
\noindent\textbf{T3 -- Entity bleed:} Medically valid entities from few-shot demonstrations migrate to the test patient. Highly dangerous as it is undetectable without the source dialogue.
\noindent\textbf{T4 -- Frequency inversion:} Substance use frequencies are minimized (``3-4 times/week'' $\to$ ``occasional''), impacting risk stratification.
\noindent\textbf{T5 -- Conditionality collapse:} Conditional plans (``consider biopsy if abnormal'') are rendered as definitive (``biopsy required''). 
\noindent\textbf{T6 -- Speaker misattribution:} Physician advice attributed to the patient. Common in translation where Dravidian grammatical honorifics drop out.
\noindent\textbf{T7 -- Fabricated absence assertion:} Hedging meta-statements (``no side effects reported'') generated when NMT fails to parse a symptom-rich passage.
\noindent\textbf{T8 -- Mistranslation cascade:} An IndicTrans2 error produces semantically empty English, silently eliminating content from the summary. Severe for Dravidian/Assamese.

\section{Discussion}
Our results quantify a critical structural disparity in clinical AI. At zero-shot, Dravidian language speakers face hallucination rates roughly 15 percentage points higher than English speakers. Default mitigation strategies fail: translation severely degrades performance for morphologically complex languages, and few-shot prompting universally increases hallucination. Deploying English-optimized clinical LLMs in multilingual settings without domain-matched fine-tuning produces documentation that is measurably less safe for low-resource populations.

Furthermore, our finding that same-language demonstrations degrade performance rules out cross-lingual interference as the primary failure mechanism for in-context learning. Instead, the \textit{entity bleed} phenomenon suggests a failure mode specific to domain-homogeneous clinical settings: because demonstration and test dialogues share identical medical domains, entities transfer plausibly but incorrectly. This serves as a stark warning against naively applying few-shot prompting in high-stakes, homogeneous domains.

Finally, while supervised fine-tuning effectively erases the cross-lingual performance gap, the widening divergence between Truthfulness and Safety scores under SFT reveals a critical alignment limitation. Standard SFT teaches models to produce accurate-sounding clinical content but fails to penalize dangerous omissions or conditional plan distortions. Bridging this gap requires safety-specific training signals, such as rubric-grounded reward models or reinforcement learning from clinical expert feedback.

\paragraph{Limitations.} 
Our evaluation utilizes 50 examples per language from a single dataset; larger-scale evaluations across diverse clinical specialties are necessary. We benchmark two 7B-parameter models; scaling laws and models with deeper Indic pretraining may exhibit different behaviors. Additionally, while LLM-as-a-judge provides scalable evaluation, it remains an approximation of expert clinical review, necessitating future validation with human clinicians. Finally, broader qualitative coverage could surface additional granular error types not captured in our taxonomy.

\section{Conclusion}
We evaluate the trustworthiness of multilingual clinical dialogue summarization across ten Indian languages, revealing stark limitations in standard deployment paradigms. Few-shot prompting actively degrades performance via entity bleed and template lock, while translation pipelines create a severe typological split that disproportionately harms morphologically complex Dravidian languages. Crucially, clinical safety remains below acceptable thresholds across all models and prompting conditions. 

However, supervised fine-tuning effectively erases the cross-lingual performance gap, demonstrating that poor low-resource performance is an artifact of insufficient task-specific training rather than an inherent linguistic limitation. Ultimately, safety evaluations conducted solely in English systematically mask the severe hallucination risks faced by speakers of low-resource languages. Future clinical AI frameworks must integrate multilingual, safety-aware training and evaluation standards before real-world deployment.

